<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 94 / International Company News: American Barrick's golden
opportunity - Takeover of Lac Minerals would create biggest gold producer
outside South Africa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When American Barrick's senior managers signed up for Spanish lessons two
years ago, they had no idea what would be coming their way in the summer of
1994.
The Toronto-based gold producer was planning to expand in Latin America, and
the managers used their new linguistic skills to buy advanced exploration
properties, and to tie up joint ventures with small resource companies.
Barrick has put down roots in this way in Peru, Bolivia, Argentina,
Venezuela and Chile.
These ventures are dwarfed, however, by the assets Barrick will acquire
thanks to its apparent victory in the seven-week takeover battle for Lac
Minerals, another Canadian gold producer. Lac's crown jewel is its 83 per
cent interest in the El Indio mine and adjacent deposits in northern Chile,
whose ambitious expansion plans could make it one of the world's premier
gold mining areas.
Mr Peter Munk, Barrick's chairman, claimed victory on Wednesday after Lac's
directors agreed to a sweetened offer consisting of cash and Barrick shares
worth an estimated CDollars 2.2bn (USDollars 1.6bn).
Lac isn't quite in Mr Munk's bag yet. Its shares are widely dispersed, with
many in the hands of unpredictable arbitrageurs.
A rival bid by Royal Oak Mines of Vancouver is, on paper, worth more than
the Barrick offer. Barrick's shares are widely considered, however, to be
more attractive and more liquid than those of the much smaller Royal Oak.
Rumours also persist that another contender may still emerge. Echo Bay
Mines, a gold producer based in Denver, Colorado, is most often mentioned.
Mr Jim Pitblado, Lac's chairman, acknowledges that his board will have to
withdraw its support from Barrick if a better offer materialises.
Barrick's bid could falter if only a third of the shares are withheld when
its offer expires on September 6. In that event, Barrick would probably
extend its bid in the hope that more shares would trickle in.
But Mr Munk is sufficiently confident of eventual success that he appeared
with Mr Pitblado on Wednesday to spell out his vision of the combined
company's future.
Less than a decade ago, Barrick was a struggling resources company, unable
even to retain the services of some of Canada's leading securities firms. It
has grown into one of North America's biggest and most profitable gold
producers, due mainly to its canny acquisition in 1987 of the Goldstrike
mine in Nevada, and a prescient policy of hedging its production against
falls in the bullion price.
Goldstrike's output has jumped from 40,000 ozs in 1987 to an estimated 1.7m
ozs this year, or about 90 per cent of Barrick's total production. But
development work at Goldstrike is now largely complete. That leaves a team
of skilled mining engineers looking for new challenges, and Barrick looking
for an outlet for the USDollars 1m in cash flowing in from Goldstrike each
day.
'American Barrick built its business in North America,' Mr Munk says. 'It
doesn't have a large inventory of offshore properties where it can focus on
future growth.'
In addition to its growing interest in Latin America, Barrick has expanded
its presence in east Asia. It has an exploration office in Beijing and
earlier this summer opened another in Jakarta. It has also been sniffing
around west Africa.
The addition of Lac - assuming investors tender their shares - will boost
Barrick's annual gold output from an estimated 1.9m ozs this year to about
3m ozs, making it the biggest producer outside South Africa. If Lac's
present expansion plans come to fruition, the combined total would rise to
more than 3.5m ozs by 1997.
However, Barrick has indicated that it will probably sell Lac's Canadian
mines. Although they generate sizeable cash flows, these properties have
little growth potential. These sales, as well as Royal Oak's obvious
interest in acquisitions, could substantially redraw the North American gold
mining industry in coming months.
El Indio is another story. In an effort to impress shareholders, Lac last
month raised its estimate of proven, probable and 'possible' reserves at El
Indio and the nearby Nevada property from 3.6m to 9.7m ozs. It has already
given the go-ahead for a USDollars 168m mine at Nevada. A bigger expansion
is on the cards if the new reserve figures are verified.
The rationale behind the takeover battle for Lac, which was initiated by
Royal Oak on July 7, was that the Toronto company has in the past failed to
make the best of its opportunities. While Barrick's share price has
multiplied almost seven times in the past five years, Lac's has remained
flat.
Lac responded to the criticism by dumping its chief executive, Mr Peter
Allen, and stepping up its expansion plans.
Barrick is likely to continue the house-cleaning. It noted in its offer
document that 'there will be significant opportunities for corporate and
operational synergies and economies as the two businesses are brought
together'.
One question mark is the future of Mr Peter Steen, brought in as Lac's new
chief executive less than a month ago from Homestake Mining of San
Francisco. It is difficult to visualise the no-nonsense Mr Steen working
with Mr Bob Smith, Barrick's earthy president.
One Lac insider who will be happy to see the end of the saga is Mr Pitblado.
Formerly head of RBC Dominion Securities, Canada's biggest securities firm,
Mr Pitblado was a non-executive Lac director until he was catapulted into
the chairman's seat by Mr Allen's departure. Mr Pitblado says he wants to
get back to his cottage on Stoney Lake, north-east of Toronto, to resume his
interrupted summer holiday.
