<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 94 / International Company News: Role in KPN flotation helps lift
ABN Amro
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ABN Amro, the largest bank in the Netherlands, posted a 14.3 per cent rise
in first-half net profit, helped in part by its leading role in the June
bourse flotation of KPN, the Dutch telecommunications and postal company.
Net profit rose to Fl 1.16bn (Dollars 670m) from Fl 1.01bn, on total revenue
up 7.7 per cent at Fl 7.46bn.
Interest income grew by 9.2 per cent to Fl 4.8bn, due to volume growth in
lending but also to a slightly higher interest rate margin overseas. At
home, the interest margin was virtually unchanged.
Commission income rose by an even stronger 14.7 per cent to Fl 1.95bn. Of
this amount, securities commission - which includes fees earned as
lead-manager of the KPN issue, the largest in Dutch corporate history - was
up 32.3 per cent at Fl 942m.
The first-half figures also showed that the bank doubled its profits in
North America, enabling it to absorb lower results posted at home and in
Europe.
Earnings per share rose by 7.1 per cent to Fl 3.45, reflecting an increase
in the number of shares outstanding. ABN Amro forecast a 'sustained'
increase in earnings per share for the full year.
In the Netherlands, pre-tax profit slipped by 5.2 per cent to Fl 945m. This
was attributed mainly to a sharp fall in results from financial
transactions.
</TEXT>
