<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 94 / Bank mortgage lending figures show 9% fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More discouraging signs in the housing market came yesterday from bank
mortgage lending figures which showed a fall in new net lending and in loans
approved in July compared with June.
The British Bankers' Association, which released the figures, said they
reflected the relative reduction in banks' market share compared with last
summer.
But these figures, with those published by the Building Societies'
Association last week, show that the number of loans approved last month -
about 83,000 - was about 10,000 fewer than the number approved in June and
about 4,000 down from the previous July.
Lenders have been saying that although recovery has been slow and fragile by
comparison with last summer there has been some advance in lending. But Mr
John Ecklin, BBA director of statistics, acknowledged that the figures were
'disappointing'.
On a seasonally adjusted basis new net lending by banks in July totalled
Pounds 593m, a fall of 9 per cent compared with Pounds 652m in June, and
below the Pounds 910m lent last July. Net lending figures take into account
repayment of principal.
Gross lending by banks in July amounted to Pounds 1.8bn, but the BBA said
that the increase from the Pounds 1.7bn June figure was probably 'more than
accounted for' by seasonal factors.
July was the month of highest mortgage lending by banks and societies last
year.
Separately, Halifax Building Society's annual survey on home improvements
shows that homeowners are preferring to use their savings to pay for home
improvements instead of increasing their mortgages or taking out loans.
