<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 94 / Lib Dems plan NHS 'rationing'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Liberal Democrats are considering a system of healthcare 'rationing'
which would make non-essential cosmetic and fertility treatments difficult
or impossible to obtain on the National Health Service.
The idea is floated in a consultation paper to be published on Monday by the
party's health policy working group.
The paper says informal rationing is already operating in the health
service, mainly through long waiting lists for certain kinds of treatment,
but there is a case for 'rational priority setting' of the kind introduced
in some US states and New Zealand.
It suggests treatment priorities could be established through public
consultation after the costs and benefits had been clarified by medical
experts.
It does not say which conditions might cease to be covered, but the working
party is understood to have focused on areas such as tattoo removal and
advanced fertility treatments.
Priority setting would be accompanied by a shift of NHS resources into
preventive healthcare, combined with a health tax and 'transparent' NHS
accounting to show the annual costs of different forms of treatment.
Members of the working party believe this would increase public pressure for
a reduction in 'self-inflicted' illnesses such as those caused by smoking.
</TEXT>
