<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 94 / Support grows for fishing treaty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
There is 'overwhelming' support among governments for a binding
international treaty to preserve the world's fish stocks, the chairman of a
United Nations conference said yesterday.
But the failure of the two-week meeting to reach consensus was sharply
criticised by environmentalists. Greenpeace called draft proposals generated
by the meeting 'too little too late'.
The conference comes after a year of fierce international clashes over
disputed fishing rights and fishing methods in nearly every ocean. Improved
technology helped the annual catch of fish to rise fivefold between 1950 and
1989 to 91m tonnes, UN figures indicate. But countries worldwide report that
catch sizes now appear to be falling because of depleted stocks.
The draft text issued yesterday from the conference on 'straddling and
highly migratory fish stocks' asks countries 'to conserve and sustainably
manage fish stocks'. It recommends creation of regional organisations to set
limits on the size of national catches, and a compulsory arbitration
procedure to resolve disputes.
Most conflicts have flared over fish that travel through the high seas
rather than national waters. Migratory fish such as tuna travel thousands of
kilometres, while 'straddling' fish, such as cod, herring and some squid,
travel back and forth from coastal waters into international zones.
Controversy at the meeting has centred on compliance and enforcement, with
Japan, North Korea and Russia expressing most unease. But Mr Satya Nandan,
Fiji ambassador to the UN and conference chairman, said the required backing
of two-thirds of delegates 'is achievable' as 'the overwhelming majority
want a binding solution'.
UN officials said although the meeting had not reached consensus,
considerable progress had been made since the last session in March, when
governments had clashed over much of the draft text. Delegates were hopeful
yesterday that the next session in March could agree on a binding treaty.
</TEXT>
