<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 94 / US leads fresh surge in markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN THOMPSON and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Equity markets on both sides of the Atlantic surged yesterday in the wake of
further encouraging economic news from the US this week.
The FT-SE 100 index of leading UK stocks rose 30.9 to 3,265.1 - its highest
closing level since mid-March - rounding off a week of strong gains that
have left the index up 2.2 per cent.
On Wall Street higher bond prices, encouraging economic news, a firmer
dollar and heavy computerised program buying lifted the Dow Jones Industrial
Average 51.16 to 3,881.05, a level not seen since mid-March. After the Dow's
25-point rise on Tuesday and Wednesday's 70-point surge, the average of
blue-chip stocks has risen 125 points, or 3.3 per cent, since Monday.
This week's buying was the most sustained on Wall Street since the Federal
Reserve began raising interest rates in February in an attempt to restrain
inflation.
Yesterday's gains were mainly due to a jump in US government bond prices
prompted by only a slight upwards revision of second quarter economic growth
estimates to 3.8 per cent. Traders had feared a larger upward revision would
make a further rise in interest rates more likely.
Frankfurt ended a cautious week by posting a 1.6 per cent rise in
post-bourse trading. Paris went 1.8 per cent higher, and Zurich rose 1.2 per
cent.
