<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Canadian wood industry faces
pay strike threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The IWA-Canada union, representing British Columbia's wood workers, has
demanded pay increases totalling 18 per cent over the next three years.
The employers' group, Forest Industrial Relations, immediately dismissed the
demand as 'out of line' and far from reflecting recent pay settlements
generally in Canada.
The union, which last week won a strike mandate from its members, said the
industry was making large profits and could afford a good increase.
'Its a stand-off and we're not sure we'll amend our position,' said Mr Gerry
Stoney, IWA-Canada president. No negotiations are scheduled yet.
</TEXT>
