<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Government Bonds: Bunds take inflation data in their stride
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The German government bond market took the widely-expected rise in August
inflation to a year-on-year rate of 3 per cent in its stride. Higher oil
prices are believed to have caused the rise.
'The market was prepared for 3 per cent . . . but the rise does not change
the view that German inflation is still falling, albeit more slowly than
before,' said Ms Wendy Niffikeer, senior economist at IBJ International. She
noted that in the cash market, 10-year yields dropped from 7.28 per cent at
the opening to 7.23 per cent in the late afternoon.
The market was also supported by comments from Mr Guntram Palm, a member of
the Bundesbank's governing board, that the central bank was not unduly
worried by the acceleration in inflation and that domestic factors spoke for
a further reduction in inflation. These comments were interpreted by some
dealers as suggesting that one more discount rate cut was possible after
all.
On Liffe, the September bund future was stuck in a narrow 28-basis point
trading range. In late trading it stood 0.26 point higher at 91.63 in
moderate trading.
UK gilts continued their steady climb, reflecting the ever-stronger view
among analysts that the market's favourable fundamentals would result in
further gains over the coming months. Gilts were also supported by the
numerous leaks from the Confederation of British Industry's monthly trends
inquiry for August which is due to be published today. On Liffe, the long
gilt future rose  3/4 point to 101 19/32 in the late afternoon.
Yesterday's publication of the weekly notes in circulation were also seen as
positive for the market. Mr Simon Briscoe at SG Warburg said the rise of 6.2
per cent in the week to August 24 meant that he would be looking for MO to
rise by just 0.3 per cent in August. This would bring the annualised
three-month rate down below 6 per cent which compared with 8 per cent in
May.
The Bank of England took advantage of the recent healthy demand for
index-linked gilts by offering Pounds 250m of index-linked Treasury stock
for sale. By contrast, dealers said the vast proportion of the Pounds 500m
worth of conventional stock on offer was still unsold because its price was
thought to be around one point too high for the market.
US Treasury bonds yesterday afternoon gave back all of the gains struck in
Wednesday's big rally.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was down 15/16 at
99 17/32 , with the yield rising to 7.533 per cent. At the short end, the
two-year note was down  3/32 at 100, to yield 6.233 per cent.
A mild downturn was not unexpected at the opening, in view of the surprising
strength shown by bonds the previous session. True to form, prices eroded
during the morning amid a round of light profit-taking. Still, the
optimistic tone which had infused the market on Wednesday showed no signs of
dissipating.
The mood turned by the afternoon. Prices began dropping soon after midday in
activity led by the futures market. An expected wave of follow-through
buying from retail accounts, which had come off the sidelines to participate
in Wednesday's successful five-year note auction, never materialised.
As a result, bonds, especially on the long end of the yield curve, were
showing big losses as the session was drawing to a close.
The sudden reversal was nearly as big a surprise as the rally had been.
</TEXT>
<XX>
