<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / International Company News: Nynex seeks waiver from 1984
order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nynex, the New York based 'Baby Bell' regional telephone company, has asked
the US justice department for an exemption from the provisions of a 1984
court order that barred the regional operators from the long-distance
telephone business.
In its filing to the justice department, Nynex argued that the widespread
competition among local telephone service providers in the New York region
meant that the company had already met most of the tough standards federal
policy makers are considering before they would allow the Baby Bells into
the long distance business.
Congress is deliberating bills to allow the Baby Bells into the
long-distance business, but the passage of any legislation still appears to
be a long way off. Nynex's action adds to the pressure for quick action to
deregulate the long-distance market. The company's request for a waiver,
however, is unlikely to speed up the process.
</TEXT>
