<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / International Company News: NEC closer to IBM standard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEC, the Japanese electronics company, is considering introducing
IBM-compatible machines in its domestic computer range for the first time.
The move highlights the growing influence of IBM's standard in the Japanese
market.
NEC said that it was looking into the possibility of introducing
IBM-compatible high-end servers based on the Pentium microprocessor made by
Intel. Servers are the machines which store data that can be shared among
several computers and link them in a network.
It is an important shift in NEC's strategy for the domestic market, where
its proprietary PCs have more than a 50 per cent share of all installed
machines.
NEC has jealously guarded the turf won by its proprietary PCs, refusing to
introduce IBM-compatible PCs in Japan even while other Japanese competitors,
with their own proprietary machines, have done so one by one.
NEC said it was considering the introduction of IBM-compatible high-end
servers in order to meet the needs of its customers. These servers would be
aimed at companies wanting to link up 20 or more computers in the office.
Office servers can cost anywhere from Y1m to hundreds of millions of yen,
and the Japanese market for high-end servers amounted to Y508bn (Dollars
5.16bn) last year.
The shift in NEC's strategy reflects the spreading acceptance in Japan of
IBM's architecture, which is a de facto standard in the rest of the world
but has been slow to catch on in Japan where Japanese computer companies
have promoted their own proprietary standards.
The company emphasised, however, that it had no plans to introduce
IBM-compatible PC servers.
</TEXT>
