<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / International Company News: Recovery continues at Bayer with
30% gain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The recovery at Bayer, the large German chemicals group, continued with a 30
per cent rise in second-quarter earnings and a 24 per cent advance for the
half-year.
The group, which started the year predicting a profits advance of up to 20
per cent for the full 12 months, yesterday reported pre-tax income for the
first half of DM999m (Dollars 624m) on sales up 6 per cent at DM22bn.
Rival Hoechst, which published its interim figures earlier this week, said
pre-tax earnings had risen 39 per cent to DM1bn on barely-changed sales.
Profits at BASF rose 41 per cent in the half.
Bayer, like its competitors, yesterday indicated falling prices were still a
problem.
Turnover at Bayer AG, the German parent, was unchanged because a 4 per cent
drop in prices cancelled out 7 per cent volume growth. The sales figure was
also diluted by the transfer of the fibres business into another part of the
group.
Turnover at European subsidiaries edged upwards to DM13bn, while North
America recorded a 9 per cent sales rise. The Asia-Pacific and African
regions advanced 19 per cent.
All operational sectors contributed to the recovery, with chemicals growing
particularly strongly. Healthcare improved 8 per cent, while growth in
consumer products sales, mainly in the Agfa film and tape business, was
limited to 2 per cent. Bayer blamed poor domestic demand.
The group attributed part of the profits progress to higher capacity use and
cost-saving measures of the past few years. As with the other German
chemicals concerns, Bayer has continued pruning costs, especially in its
domestic operations.
The total workforce fell 2,600 in the review period and the rise in
personnel costs was limited to 2 per cent in spite of higher social security
costs and adverse exchange rate movements.
</TEXT>
