<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Body Shop spillage details revealed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Body Shop International, the cosmetics and toiletries group, was pursued by
local US environmental authorities in connection with four separate releases
of liquids from its New Jersey plant in the last two years.
The details of its environmental performance appear to contradict statements
it has released in the last few days as pressure has grown over its green
and ethical image.
Body Shop was responsible for at least three releases into the sewage system
which were detected initially by the local sewage authority, a senior
official of the authority said yesterday.
In a letter, published in the Financial Times on Wednesday, Mr Gordon
Roddick, Body Shop's chairman, said there had been two spills from its New
Jersey warehouse of 30 gallons of shampoo two years ago after which it
'immediately notified the authorities'.
However, documents obtained by the Financial Times show that the company
released a total of at least 62 gallons of shampoo or shower gel in three
spills, two in 1992 and another in 1993.
On each occasion, it was officials of the Hanover Sewage Authority who
identified the releases and traced them back to the Body Shop.
In another incident in 1993, Body Shop notified the authorities immediately
when sub-contractors hired while it was cleaning its warehouse emptied
adhesive remover chemicals into the system.
Mr Michael Wynne, executive director of the authority, said yesterday: 'It
should have been relatively easy for them to comply with our regulations.
They kept saying they were going to move.'
He said Body Shop provided assurances that it would improve its systems
after the first incident, but after two more it decided to issue it with a
permit.
He said he believed that the spills were readily preventable, and that there
should have been time for Body Shop to identify them and notify the
authority before its officers did.
Body Shop yesterday said it was aware of two spills totalling 60 gallons and
the release of the cleaning chemicals, but that while it was difficult to
determine the exact sequence of notification the spills were insignificant.
'We have never said we are a perfect company. This is a small incident in
the life of a worldwide company. Things like this do happen,' it said.
</TEXT>
