<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Ladbroke to unveil return to casinos with results details
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ladbroke, the hotels, bookmakers, and DIY group, is expected to announce its
return to the UK casino market next week, 15 years after being expelled from
the business.
The group is believed to be planning to announce the acquisition of three
London casinos for about Pounds 50m when it reveals its interim results on
Thursday.
The purchase has been the subject of some speculation, with uncertainty over
approval from the Gaming Board of Ladbroke's fitness to run casinos. The
company was forced to give up its casinos in 1979 after allegations of
malpractice over its attempts to win business.
One industry source said he would be 'astonished' if the acquisition was not
unveiled on Thursday, adding that that the company would be 'stupid' to go
ahead with the acquisition unless it was confident it could get gaming board
approval.
Changes in the law since 1979 could work in Ladbroke's favour. Previously,
companies would be licensed. Now, however, individuals are licensed. The
retirement earlier this year of Mr Cyril Stein, chairman at the time of the
expulsion, leaves Ladbroke with a new management to apply for licenses.
Ladbroke is understood to be in discussions with leisure operator, Mr Trevor
Hemmings, over the exact price for his City Clubs group. It is expected to
pay at least Pounds 50m for the up-market Maximes, middle-market Golden
Horseshoe, and the popular Charlie Chester's casinos.
Analysts said this appeared to be a high price for a company with sales of
about Pounds 100m and pre-tax profits estimated at Pounds 5m.
However, the acquisition was merely a means to an end, said one analyst: 'I
have been expecting Ladbroke to overpay for a London casino for some time.'
Ladbroke's ambitions to expand in the growing international casino market
could be hindered by its chequered past. Returning to the UK market, where
the gaming regulations are seen to be strict would give the group
credibility abroad.
Analysts are expecting Ladbroke to post pre-tax profits on Thursday of about
Pounds 50m for the first half, against Pounds 62.5m last time.
</TEXT>
