<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Undaunted by hit to newspaper profits: A UK price war that
looks set to continue into next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
News International, Mr Rupert Murdoch's main UK operating company, has set
its sights on taking The Times to a circulation of more than 1m. In a
further indication that price wars in the UK national newspaper industry are
likely to continue, Mr Gus Fischer, News International's chief executive,
said: 'Obviously we would like to push it (The Times) to the same level as
The Telegraph and beyond.'
The 20p Times has increased its circulation by more than 200,000 to its
current level of approaching 600,000 and The Daily Telegraph, after reducing
its cover price to 30p on weekdays, has increased its circulation from
993,000 to about 1.07m copies.
'We think we have proved beyond any shadow of a doubt that newspapers are
price sensitive,' Mr Fischer said yesterday. He insisted that pricing policy
would be kept continually under review.
However, in a sign that News International is growing increasingly confident
in its current pricing policy, the newspaper group - which owns five UK
national newspapers - said it was increasing its advertising rates by 15 per
cent on three of them.
The rates are increasing on both the Sun, now selling at 22p, and the Times.
The group will give advertisers a guaranteed 600,000 circulation for The
Times until the end of this year and a 4m guarantee for the Sun. The latter
is selling around 4.2m despite this week's 2p price increase. The Sun's
price was cut from 25p to 20p last summer.
Advertising rates are also increasing by 15 per cent on the News of the
World, although there is no sign that News International plans to reduce the
price of its popular Sunday tabloid or its other market-leading title, The
Sunday Times.
Although News International could give advertisers rebates if the minimum
circulation guarantees are not met, the move on rates implies that the
newspaper price war is likely to last for the rest of this year and probably
well into next.
This means continuing difficulties for The Telegraph group, which admitted
on Wednesday that its price cut had cost Pounds 1m for just the first six
days included in its latest reporting period. In addition, discount vouchers
had cost Pounds 1m and Pounds 8m had been spent on promotion.
News International's commitment to its radical pricing policy emerged as the
News Corp subsidiary announced its results for the year to the end of June.
Its operating profits of Pounds 96.2m fell Pounds 44.7m below its 1992-93
performance. The main reason for the difference was the impact of the price
cuts, but News International declined to give the precise figure
attributable to the pricing policy.
Mr Fischer said: 'The UK newspaper industry market has never been so
competitive and I can't see that changing.'
News International's turnover increased from Pounds 708.1m to Pounds 733.5m
and profit after minorities soared from Pounds 146.4m to Pounds 359.3m.
The large increase was, however, attributable to a number of non-operating
factors. A Pounds 78.6m contribution from associates came largely from
BSkyB, the satellite television venture 50 per cent owned by News Corp.
There was also a book profit of Pounds 90m on the disposal of fixed assets -
the transfer within the group, it is believed, of shares in Reuters, the
news and information group, and in Pearson, owner of the Financial Times.
Net interest income amounted to Pounds 85.9m, up from Pounds 1.6m, again
helped by transactions within the group.
Special dividend shareholders of News International will receive a final
dividend of the sterling equivalent of 1.5 Australian cents a share.
