<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / GRE doubles its trading profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Guardian Royal Exchange, the composite insurance company, provided more
evidence of the strong recovery in the UK general insurance market when it
announced interim trading profits of Pounds 131m, doubled from Pounds 65m
last year.
After taking into account net realised and unrealised investment losses of
Pounds 417m, the group reported a pre-tax loss of Pounds 286m, against a
profit of Pounds 307m. Unlike its main competitors, GRE includes capital
gains and losses in its profit and loss account.
Mr John Robins, the group's new chief executive, said the decision to
increase the interim dividend by 7.5 per cent to 2.85p (2.65p) reflected
'not only the group's trading performance worldwide but also its sound
balance sheet and strong cash generation'.
A UK underwriting profit of Pounds 24m was 'the engine behind the
improvement', said Mr James Morley, finance director. Underwriting profits
of Pounds 47m, up from break-even last year, were achieved on home, motor
and other personal lines business, offsetting a Pounds 10m loss (Pounds 24m
loss) on commercial lines and a Pounds 13m loss (Pounds 16m loss) in the
London market.
Results benefited from premium rate increases, more selective underwriting
and improved claims experience. In its motor business, frequency of claims
has fallen from 30 for every 100 cars insured in 1991 to less than 25 in
June 1994.
Mr Morley said Guardian Direct, the telephone insurer launched in March,
received premium income of Pounds 2m against expenses and claims of Pounds
8m.
GRE's German operations cut its loss from Pounds 28m to Pounds 15m. Losses
were also reduced in Canada and Ireland, but increased in the US South
Africa.
Life profits rose to Pounds 13m (Pounds 11m), but the group is continuing to
reorganise its life businesses, following the loss of more than 300 jobs in
the past 12 months. Net investment income rose to Pounds 150m (Pounds 149m).
The decline in the equity and fixed income markets during the first six
months led to fall in the value of shareholders funds. These amounted to
Pounds 1.39bn by June 30, compared with Pounds 1.35bn at the same stage last
year and Pounds 1.68bn at December 31. Overall premium income amounted to
Pounds 2.01bn (Pounds 1.77bn).
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
