<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / BSkyB and Ansett help lift News Corp 24%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A surge in profits from its two associate companies, BSkyB and Ansett
Airlines, more than offset a small decline in earnings from core operations
at News Corporation, and allowed Mr Rupert Murdoch's media and film group to
post after-tax profits, before abnormals, of ADollars 1.21bn (Pounds 580m)
in the 12 months to June.
This was nearly 24 per cent up on the ADollars 979m made in the previous
year. Net profits after abnormals reached ADollars 1.33bn, up from ADollars
864m. This reflected a ADollars 123m gain - largely on the sale of the
group's interest in the South China Morning Post (SCMP) - compared with a
ADollars 115m charge last time. Revenues were 8.7 per cent higher at
ADollars 11.6bn.
Much of the improvement came from the two associates, whose combined
contribution to profits more than doubled from ADollars 177m to ADollars
394. Ansett, the Australian airline owned jointly by News Corp and TNT, saw
operating profits almost quadruple, while passenger volume rose by more than
13 per cent.
The airline attributed the improvement to increased business travel, better
yield management, advertising and cost control. BSkyB, the satellite
broadcaster in which News has a 50 per cent stake and where Pearson,
publisher of the Financial Times, also has a stake, saw operating profits
rise 170 per cent.
News Corp's figures were also helped by a ADollars 70m drop in interest
charges, to ADollars 667m, as a debt reduction and rescheduling programme
continued.
Operating profits from core operations were 6.2 per cent lower at ADollars
1.6bn, with strong increases on the film and television side offset by
declines in newspapers and magazines/inserts. The latter was due to the
newspaper price war in the UK, which cut operating profits there by 37 per
cent; to the sale of the SCMP interest; to higher than expected start-up
costs at a new Melbourne printing facility; and to competitive pressure in
the coupon industry.
Overall, the newspapers division made operating profits of ADollars 436m,
against ADollars 671m, while magazines and inserts contributed ADollars
339m, against ADollars 402m.
By contrast, the film division multiplied operating profits to ADollars
141m, from ADollars 53m, while television made ADollars 466m against
ADollars 373m. The book publishing side produced ADollars 208m.
Earnings per share, based on profits after outside equity interests but
before abnormal items, rose 12.3 per cent to 64 cents.
Lex, Page 14; BSkyB, Page 17
</TEXT>
