<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Clinton wins vital Senate support for Dollars 30bn crime
bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton won a crucial victory yesterday when Democrats and
moderate Republicans in the Senate united to pass a procedural motion paving
the way for a vote on the controversial Dollars 30bn (Pounds 19.3bn) crime
bill.
If the bill is approved in a final vote, the president will get a
much-needed boost as he struggles to revive his flagging political standing
ahead of mid-term Congressional elections in November. Senators were poised
last night to vote in further stages of the legislative process.
The crime bill, which was passed by the House of Representatives on Sunday,
has seemed in danger of being lost through procedural wrangling in the
Senate.
But the president's supporters mustered 61 votes - just one more than
necessary under the rules - to get the bill over a critical initial hurdle.
Six Republicans joined 55 Democrats to push the bill ahead, while 38
Republicans and one Democrat were opposed.
After a final vote is taken on the crime bill, the Senate will adjourn for
two weeks, but behind-the-scenes efforts will try to make progress on
healthcare - Mr Clinton's other big legislative goal.
The crime bill would provide funding over six years for new prisons, extra
police and social programmes aimed at preventing people from turning to
crime.
The crime bill has been caught up in blocking manoeuvres by the Republicans
with an eye to the looming elections. Last year a similar bill passed the
Senate by a wide margin of 95-4, with only two Republicans in opposition.
That bill went to a House-Senate conference committee, where differences
between the House and Senate versions were ironed out. But when the bill
returned for a final vote, it nearly failed in the House and has run into
strong Republican blocking tactics in the Senate.
Republican Senators have tried to eliminate the social programmes from the
bill. But Democrats have accused them of acting on behalf of the powerful
gun lobby, which wants the bill killed because it contains a ban on assault
weapons.
The crime bill was intended as a showcase for Mr Clinton's brand of moderate
government activism. It contains items to appeal to various constituencies:
new death penalties, tougher sentencing laws, incentives for the hiring of
100,000 new policemen, and prison funding - all intended to appeal to the
political right; crime prevention programmes for the political left; and the
assault weapons ban to demonstrate that Washington is not in the grip of
'special interests'.
On the Senate floor yesterday, the Democratic leader, Senator George
Mitchell, begged his colleagues to 'resist the temptation to take a
political action' by opposing the bill.
The lengthy wrangling over the crime bill has held up Senate action on
healthcare reforms and some Democrats claim that is the real purpose of the
Republican tactics.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
    P92   Justice, Public Order, and Safety.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
