FT  26 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is usually at 9.00 or 9.30 that programme clashes occur and you have to
resort to the VCR, but today it happens at 8.00. BBC2 shows My Name Is
Albert Watson, a profile of one of the world's top - though little known -
photographers. Born in Scotland and living in the US, Watson has 70 Vogue
covers to his credit and some of the best known photographs of rock stars
including the Rolling Stones. At the same time Channel 4 screens the last in
the current series of dance programmes, Tights, Camera, Action] Lea Anderson
introduces her own choreography in La Spectre da la Rose. Also at 8.00 on
BBC1 Jonathan Ross Presents David Copperfield. This will serve as a handy
puff for the American conjuror who is bringing his show to London this
autumn. And we should not forget The Bill, one of television's most
consistent drama series though not, as some seem to imagine, a 'soap' (8.00
ITV). Tarantula omelettes are never going to catch on, but the Survival
Special which gives news of the dish may well get a big rating, spiders
being one of those creatures, it seems, that viewers love to hate (9.00
ITV).
