<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Hand movement restored
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW DERRINGTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Surgeons at Salisbury District Hospital plan 12 operations to restore hand
movement to patients paralysed by spinal injury, writes Andrew Derrington.
Implanted electrodes will stimulate muscles that have been disconnected from
the brain. In some cases muscle tendons will be transplanted to give better
control. The stimulator will be controlled by shrugging the opposite
shoulder.
The operations at Salisbury are part of a larger test series, co-ordinated
from the US, says Jack Gardner of Inspire Foundation, which is paying for
the electronic equipment.
Inspire Foundation: UK, tel 0722 336262 ext 2465; fax 0722 336550
