<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Slow but sure pension sea-change: Long-term movement in
policies' popularity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At first sight the new business figures released by the Association of
British Insurers yesterday are like gently rolling English countryside,
generally flat but with some slight valleys.
On closer inspection, however, they reveal longer-term changes which have a
more significant influence on the personal pensions and life insurance
landscape.
There are three trends which are highlighted by the figures for the second
quarter of this year - the shift from regular to single premium policies, a
move away from products which are not linked to equity investments, and a
marked decline in sales through home collections.
The reluctance of customers to take on long-term commitments is behind the
trend towards single-premium policies. The number of yearly premium life
insurance policies has been falling since 1991, when 5.29m were taken out.
About 4.64m were taken out last year.
The total is fewer than 2m for the first half of this year.
Numbers of regular premium personal pensions have similarly fallen, from
1.56m in 1991 to 1.28m last year. Only about 563,000 have been sold in the
first six months of this year.
By contrast, sales of single premium life insurance policies have held up
rather better. Although the 276,000 policies and Pounds 2.4bn new premiums
for the second quarter are below the comparable figures for the second
quarter last year, they are higher than the equivalent figures in 1991.
This changing balance between regular and single premium policies has been
apparent from the new business figures reported from large life insurers
such as Legal &amp; General.
Further below the surface has been the shift towards 'linked' policies in
the types of investment that are preferred by customers, which is revealed
by the ABI statistics.
Linked policies - which can be life insurance products or pensions - are
policies where part of the premiums buy investment units, for example in an
equity or property portfolio, which are managed by a fund manager. Their
value can fluctuate but there is the prospect of higher returns to make up
for the risk that the value when the policy reaches maturity will be lower
than the payout from a conventional policy.
Non-linked policies are generally invested in gilts or deposits, where both
the risk and potential returns are lower, but the value of the policy is
raised by bonuses from the profits of the fund during the course of its
life, culminating in a terminal bonus.
The ABI figures show that the steepest falls in business in a comparison
between the second quarter of this year and last year have been in
non-linked policies.
New premiums from linked annual and single-premium individual pensions and
from linked single-premium life insurance were broadly similar in the period
from April to the end of June in 1993 and 1994, but premiums in non-linked
products in the same categories fell by up to 35 per cent from their 1993
levels.
The figures also confirm a clear shift in how life insurance is sold.
Policies sold through the 'industrial branch' - where a sales agent calls
once every two weeks or so at the home of a customer to collect what are
often relatively small premiums - have plummeted.
At 201,000 policies and Pounds 28m new premium income for the second
quarter, both sets of numbers are now less than half the equivalent just two
years ago.
Concerns among life companies such as Prudential about the cost of
collecting premiums from customers' homes mean that industrial branch
business is likely to continue to diminish.
Customers' fears about job prospects are likely to mean that the shift away
from regular premium products is likely to continue so long as memories of
the most recent recession remain fresh.
Life companies must hope that the trend to linked policies, which the ABI
says shows a confidence in the life companies' investment performance, is
similarly persistent to offset the other changes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
