<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / West Coast rail plan to cost Pounds 500m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Modernisation plans for the 550-mile West Coast main railway are unlikely to
lead to construction of a high-speed line on the French model because of the
cost and the likelihood of environmental protests.
But Mr Gil Howarth, Railtrack's director of major projects, said yesterday
that the introduction of '21st-century signalling' with modest changes to
the present route should still lead to significant reductions in journey
times.
The Pounds 500m upgrading of the West Coast route, last modernised in the
1970s, is expected to reduce the London to Glasgow journey from six to four
hours, London to Manchester or Liverpool from 2 3/4 to two hours, and London
to Birmingham from two to 1 1/4 hours. These times should prove competitive
with airline schedules.
The West Coast line is one of the busiest in the UK, carrying more than
2,000 trains a day. InterCity expresses account for 16 per cent of train
journeys although they cover 80 per cent of the mileage travelled.
The likely design of the line has emerged from a 'second sift' of options
carried out by a 60-strong project team consisting of staff of Railtrack and
WCML Development, a private-sector consortium involved in the feasibility
study. A third review will take place in October in time for final proposals
to be put to the government before Christmas.
A construction consortium will be selected by competitive tender to start
work next year. Depending on the degree of disruption acceptable to existing
services, modernisation will take between four and eight years.
Local authorities and business interests along the line have been pressing
for it to be upgraded to speeds of 125mph to 185mph. It appears top speeds
will be at the lower end of this range, but improved journey times can still
be gained by track realignment and modifications to narrow tunnels.
Significant improvements will result from the upgrading of signalling. The
latest airline-style radio-operated system, which does away with track-side
signals, could be used on the fastest sections of track. A more conventional
system would operate around big cities.
Mr Howarth said it would be possible for InterCity services to be controlled
over the entire route by a single signalling centre but two or three centres
were more likely. This is likely to lead to a reduction in the number of
signalling staff.
A decision has yet to be taken on whether new rolling stock will be provided
for the line - at a further likely cost of Pounds 300m to Pounds 400m -
although the more modern the track and signalling systems, the more likely
it becomes that new trains will be needed. One option being considered is
tilting trains similar to those in Sweden and Spain.
The private sector is expected to contribute most of the cost of the project
 -in return for a concession to operate the line - although public funds
will also be needed. Present government thinking is for the line to be
financed through a subsidy for the train operators' track-access charges
rather than by a grant to meet capital costs.
The consortium which wins the contract will probably be expected to take
responsibility for maintaining the track.
</TEXT>
<XX>
