<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Pollard quits at Sunday Express
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The husband and wife editing team of Sir Nicholas Lloyd at the Daily Express
and his wife at the Sunday Express was split yesterday with the abrupt
resignation of Lady Lloyd, Ms Eve Pollard.
Ms Pollard, the former editor of the Sunday Mirror who was appointed editor
of the Sunday Express in May 1991, is 'to go in search of other interests'.
In an agreed statement Ms Pollard agreed to remain a consultant to Express
Newspapers.
Mr Brian Hitchen, a former deputy editor of the Sunday Express and present
editor of the Daily Star, takes over as editor of the Sunday Express on
September 1.
Mr Hitchen, who has for many years wanted to edit the Sunday Express, takes
on one of the most difficult jobs in national newspapers - trying to reverse
the apparently remorseless long-term decline in the paper's circulation.
During Ms Pollard's editorship the Sunday Express became a tabloid and there
have been periods of rising circulation. Trying to displace the the
influence of the Mail on Sunday has proved more difficult.
The vacancy at the Daily Star prompted speculation that Mr Kelvin MacKenzie
might fill the chair. The former editor of The Sun recently resigned
abruptly from the managing director's job at BSkyB, the satellite television
broadcaster, after losing a power struggle with Mr Sam Chisholm, chief
executive.
However, it is thought unlikely at United Newspapers, owner of the Daily
Star, that Mr MacKenzie will move to the newspaper. An internal appointment
is thought more plausible.
In a statement yesterday Ms Pollard said she had enjoyed her years as editor
of the Sunday Express.
'It has been an exciting and innovative period but now the newspaper is in
prosperous health I think the time is right for me to seek new challenges,'
said Ms Pollard.
Lex, Page 14
BSkyB and Ansett, Page 15
