<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Archer case review rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday rejected Labour calls for a Crown Prosecution
Service review of the Department of Trade and Industry decision not to
prosecute Lord Archer for placing orders to buy Anglia Television shares.
Mr Neil Hamilton, the corporate affairs minister, said there was 'no case'
for a review of the decision by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary. The decision was 'wholly consistent' with advice from an
independent QC, taken by Mr Heseltine after he received a report on the deal
from DTI inspectors.
Mr Hamilton said in a letter to Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry
secretary: 'I therefore reject entirely any suggestion that this decision,
or indeed the decision to confirm the existence of the investigation, was
tainted by partiality.'
His letter followed an admission by Lord Archer, the Conservative peer and
best-selling novelist, that it was a 'grave error' to have placed orders to
buy shares in Anglia, of which his wife is a director, shortly before a
takeover bid.
Mr Cook said the letter left a number of unanswered questions about the
deal, including why Lord Archer did not use his usual broker.
He said: 'This is not a controversy that is going to go away quickly.
Michael Heseltine, or any other Tory minister, is not a proper person to
decide whether a senior Tory politician should face prosecution.
'So long as the decision on that is left to a Tory minister, the suspicion
will linger that political considerations played a part.'
It emerged yesterday that ministers and officials may be questioned on the
affair by the Commons trade and industry committee when parliament
reconvenes in the autumn.
</TEXT>
