<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Milk sale delayed as row deepens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The row over milk trade deregulation deepened last night after the Scottish
Milk Marketing Board agreed to postpone only the second auction of milk
under a new system when bid prices rose to unexpectedly high levels, Michael
Smith writes.
The Scottish Dairy Trade Federation, which like its English counterpart is
protesting about the changes, said the move demonstrated the inability of
the deregulated system to produce realistic prices.
However, the SMMB said there was no compulsion on bidders to offer as much
as they had and said there was no plan to reform the system. The 2.2m litres
of milk unsold yesterday, representing about half the planned total, would
be auctioned later.
The postponement of the auction coincided with a meeting over the row
between Mr William Waldegrave, agriculture minister, and the Milk Marketing
Board for England and Wales and the Dairy Trade Federation. The ministry
said last night that Mr Waldegrave had agreed to discuss the matter with
cabinet colleagues.
This week the DTF said it would challenge the government in court over its
handling of milk deregulation. Before the meeting yesterday Mr Waldegrave
said he did not rule out a referral to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
In yesterday's auction for milk in December, prices varied from 27.1p to
30.7p. Dr Donald McQueen, SDTF chief executive, said they were artificially
high because of pressure on dairies to obtain the supplies they needed. 'The
whole system has been designed to push up prices.'
Letters, Page 12
</TEXT>
