<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Directors told to reveal financial control systems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies are to be strongly urged to produce a statement describing their
internal financial controls from the start of next year.
Under draft guidelines issued yesterday directors will have to provide a
statement in the annual report and accounts stressing that they are
responsible for internal controls.
They will also be asked to provide a description of the key procedures used
by their company and how directors review the system of internal financial
control.
The guidelines were released by the working group on internal control
convened at the request of the Cadbury committee on the financial aspects of
corporate governance, comprising individuals from business and the
accountancy profession.
The Cadbury committee, which issued its report at the end of 1992, advised
companies to provide a statement of internal controls in their accounts,
which led to the creation of the working party.
Companies are not forced to comply, but any quoted business that does not
provide such a statement must note in its accounts that it fails to meet
this requirement of the Cadbury code on pain of reprimand from the Stock
Exchange.
The revised internal control guidance is significantly less detailed than an
earlier draft issued last year, which came under a barrage of criticism from
industry.
It no longer includes the suggestion that directors comment on non-financial
internal controls, or that they should provide an opinion on the
effectiveness of these controls.
The directors' statement should include the steps taken to ensure an
appropriate control environment in the company, the process used to identify
significant risks, the main information and control systems in place, and
the monitoring system used.
Mr Gerry Acher, head of audit at KPMG Peat Marwick, welcomed the simplified
new draft. He said: 'The subject of internal controls is best dealt with
between the auditor and the audit committee, not in a report. But the report
puts the onus on the audit committee to do its job.'
Comments on the draft proposals are invited before the end of October.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
