<DATELINE>
   BOMBAY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
India's central bank has lifted a ban on the repatriation of profits from
the local bond markets and encouraged investment in property companies in
twin moves designed to attract greater capital from Indians living abroad,
Reuter reports from Bombay.
The measures were included in a circular to banks following last Friday's
move to make the rupee fully convertible on current account transactions.
The Reserve Bank of India said it would let non-resident Indian companies
acquire up to a 100 per cent of companies involved in housing, real estate,
urban infrastructure, such as roads and bridges, building materials and
financing of housing development.
