<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Economic Watch: E German industrial output up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN, THE HAGUE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Eastern Germany's industrial output rose by 15 per cent in June compared to
the same period in 1993 and by 5.3 per cent compared to May, the federal
economics ministry announced yesterday. It said seasonal factors had helped
to boost overall output. However, output in individual sectors was mixed.
Manufacturing recovered strongly, up 21.5 per cent year-on-year, and by 6.7
per cent between May and June. Construction, one of the most buoyant
sectors, rose 14 per cent and 8 per cent over the same periods. Output in
the electricity and gas sectors increased only by 3.4 per cent year-on-year
and fell by 6.7 per cent between May and June. The mining sector, mostly
brown coal, or lignite, fell by 13.6 per cent year-on-year, and rose 4.4 per
cent in June compared to the previous month.
Consumer spending in the Netherlands rose 1.5 per cent in real terms in the
second quarter from last year, the Dutch Central Bureau for Statistics said
yesterday. That gain was sharply narrower than the 2.8 per cent real
increase in the first quarter.
France's current account showed a seasonally adjusted surplus of FFr1.14bn
(Pounds 130m) in May after a revised FFr2.75bn surplus in April, the economy
ministry said.
</TEXT>
