<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Germans settle property claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The German federal office for the regulation of property questions, set up
to deal with outstanding property rights claims in eastern Germany from the
Nazi and Communist eras, yesterday said it had settled 38 per cent of all
claims by last June, excluding enterprises. More than 43 per cent of all
claims for businesses had also been settled. The office, which expects to
take 10 more years clarifying the rest, originally registered 1.248m claims
for 2.8m property titles. Berlin and Saxony-Anhalt have resolved only 20 per
cent and 31 per cent respectively of all enterprise claims largely because
both regions had sizeable Jewish communities, and it has been difficult to
trace descendants. Saxony, with 62 per cent, has the highest rate of
settlement among the eastern states.
</TEXT>
