<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Russia to resettle miners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Fifty thousand Russian coalminers and their families will be resettled by
the government as their mines in northern Siberia are closed, senior coal
industry officials said yesterday. The miners live in settlements where the
pits are the only source of employment, and have little possibility of
finding alternative employment if the government resists pressure to bail
out failing state enterprises with inflationary soft loans. Mr Yuri
Malyshev, head the state coal producers' association, said 50,000 miners and
their families from the settlement of Vorkuta and the northern region as a
whole would be resettled over the next few years. However, so far only 500
families have been resettled in more hospitable southern areas. Russian coal
production was down 12 per cent in the first half of this year compared with
last year. Two thousand Russian farmers, members of the Agrarian party, and
communists demonstrated yesterday against President Boris Yeltsin and his
government, saying ill-conceived reforms were wrecking agriculture and rural
life.
</TEXT>
