<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Santer heralds change of style
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jacques Santer, incoming European Commission president, plans a more
open, less autocratic style of leadership and a wide-ranging internal
shake-up when he succeeds Mr Jacques Delors next January. Officials close to
him say he wants a more collegiate approach, ending Mr Delors' practice of
concentrating power in an inner circle and creating an underground network
in the bureaucracy. The long-time Luxembourg premier's task is being made
harder by member states' delays in putting forward candidates for
commissioners and rivalry over portfolios. In France, arguments persist
about suitable candidates. Former prime minister Edith Cresson would be
welcomed as a political heavyweight, though French claims to the external
trade portfolio are being resisted by the UK which wants Sir Leon Brittan to
retain it. Brussels officials are also worried that referendums on EU
membership in Finland, Sweden, and Norway could force delays in agreeing a
division of the Commission spoils. If enlargement goes ahead, the number of
commissioners will rise from 17 to 21 (including Austria). Mr Santer is said
to be confident enough work can be found, but others are doubtful.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BEZ  Belgium, EC.
