<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Siberian miners to be resettled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Fifty thousand Russian coal miners and their families will be resettled by
the government as their mines in northern Siberia are closed down, senior
coal industry officials said yesterday. The miners live in settlements where
the pits are the only source of employment, and have little possibility of
finding alternative employment if the government resists pressure to bail
out failing state enterprises with inflationary soft loans. Mr Yuri
Malyshev, head of Rosugol, the state coal producers' association, said that
50,000 coal miners and their families from the mining settlement of Vorkuta
and the northern region as a whole would be resettled over the next few
years. However, so far only 500 families have been resettled in more
hospitable southern areas of the country and to date Rosugol has acquired
only 1,800 flats for the mining families. Russian coal production was down
12 per cent in the first half of this year compared with last year.
Two thousand Russian farmers, members of the Agrarian party, and communists
demonstrated yesterday against President Boris Yeltsin and his government,
saying ill-conceived reforms were wrecking the nation's agriculture and
rural life. Mr Mikhail Lapshin, head of the Agrarian Party, told the rally
in Moscow that the farmers wanted fair prices for their produce, timely
payment and freedom from debts. Agriculture ministry officials say promised
funds for this year's purchases, due to be made at market prices after
negotiations, have not been made available.
</TEXT>
