<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / CBI reports rise in output but warns on prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK manufacturing output and orders are growing at their fastest rates since
the late 1980s, according to the latest Confederation of British Industry
monthly trends inquiry, but expectations of higher prices are increasing.
For the first time since April 1989, more companies believe their order
books are above normal, than below. The findings appear to confirm official
statistics earlier this week which showed that the rate of economic growth
was accelerating and would beat the Treasury's 2.75 per cent forecast for
1994.
CBI surveys deduct those reporting a decrease from those reporting an
increase to produce a percentage balance.
The balance of those expecting an increase in output over the next four
months is 30 percentage points, the highest figure since September 1988,
while the balance of those reporting above normal order books is 4
percentage points.
Financial markets are likely to watch the figure on price expectations with
the most interest, as it is seen as an important indicator of inflationary
pressures. The balance of companies expecting to raise prices over the next
four months has edged steadily up from April, and reached 15 percentage
points in August, from 12 percentage points in July. Some analysts predicted
the price expectations balance would fall from July's figure and the
increase may renew fears of a rise in base rates.
However, the CBI points out 65 per cent of companies still believe that
prices will be unchanged over the next four months, and only one in four
expects to make an increase.
The CBI also produced its revised economic forecast for 1994 and 1995. It
has upgraded its expectations for gross domestic product growth this year
from 2.4 to 3 per cent, although that forecast does not take account of the
strong GDP figures published earlier this week.
The CBI believes economic growth will slow in the second half of this year,
as the full impact of tax increases hits consumer spending, and GDP growth
in 1995 will drop back to 2.5 per cent.
The CBI believes there is no need for an immediate rate increase following
the next meeting between the chancellor, Mr Kenneth Clarke, and the governor
of the Bank of England, Mr Eddie George, on September 7.
It expects to see inflationary pressures leading to a quarter or a half
percentage point rise in base rates before the end of the year, and its
forecast assumes a further increase to 6.25 per cent by the middle of next
year.
Bonds, Page 20
Currencies, Page 23
</TEXT>
