<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 94 / Lockheed barred from exporting Hercules: Decision raises
doubts over Pounds 1bn tender to supply RAF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lockheed, the US aerospace company, has been barred indefinitely from
exporting its C-130 Hercules aircraft by the US State Department, raising
doubts about the company's Pounds 1bn bid to supply the UK with replacement
transport aircraft.
The company is accused of breaching the US Foreign Corrupt Practices Act by
bribing foreign officials on previous contracts. Lockheed is attempting to
sell 30 of the latest-generation C-130J aircraft to Britain and 12 similar
transporters to Australia.
The ban, revealed in documents filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission this week, was imposed by the State Department on August 18. It
follows the indictment in June on bribery charges of two Lockheed executives
and the company's Lockheed Aeronautical Systems Company (LASC) subsidiary,
which makes the Hercules transporter and the P-3 Orion maritime patrol
aircraft.
The scandal comes during a battle over the UK transporter order between
Lockheed and a group led by British Aerospace, which wants the Royal Air
Force to buy a European alternative.
Lockheed already has export licences for the UK deal, but the political
sensitivity of the issue would make any conviction embarrassing.
The Ministry of Defence had hoped to make a decision before the end of the
year. The C-130J is due to be in service by 1996.
The company is accused of paying an Egyptian politician, Ms Leila Takla,
Dollars 1m (Pounds 600,000) to help secure an order for three Hercules
aircraft five years ago. It denies the allegations and is contesting the
court case. The two executives accused are Mr Allen Love, formerly LASC's
director of Middle East and North African sales, and Mr Suleiman Nassar, a
Lockheed regional vice-president who operated from Geneva and is being
sought by investigators.
If convicted, Lockheed faces an indefinite ban on exports from its LASC
subsidiary until it can satisfy the State Department that practices have
been improved. Export licences granted before the June 22 indictment still
stand, and the company can appeal on a case-by-case basis for any ban to be
lifted.
Licences for potential UK and Australian exports should be unaffected by the
court case, according to the company. Even so, any conviction would raise
the political stakes in the UK of deciding to buy a US rather than a
European made transporter.
In a separate report, the US Air Force said that the C-130J would be five
months late and would be Dollars 200m over-budget.
A Lockheed spokesman said the company was happy with its estimates.
</TEXT>
