<DOCNO>FT943-6977</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EHYDMAF7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940825
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Asda active
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Turnover in food retailer ASDA Group jumped to a hefty 29.5m, making it the
day's most actively traded stock after a broker reiterated its buy
recommendation on the stock.
The shares closed 3 ahead at 67p, as Morgan Stanley reiterated its buy
stance on the stock and predicted likely profit upgradings. Mr Nick Bubb at
the broker said: 'If the stores renewal programme continues to deliver
results and industry margins continue to recover then current profits
estimates will look conservative.' His current prediction is for full-year
profits of Pounds 200m.
Investment bank Lehman brothers were also said to have been active in the
stock.
The sector has been left behind in recent sessions and dealers took the
opportunity of a strong market yesterday for bargain-hunting, thus boosting
other food retailing stocks. Kwik Save jumped 10 to 612p, Argyll Group 8 to
296p and Tesco, 4 to 249p. Tesco said yesterday it had received acceptances
for 58.11 per cent of Wm Low, the Scottish grocer at the centre of the
recent bid battle, and also claimed acceptances for 49.77 per cent of the
preference share offer.
Securities house UBS was said to have had the big buyer of WH Smith Group,
the high street retailer which reported figures in line with market
expectations yesterday.
The shares gained 12 to 481p, after trade of 2m. However, Mr Tony Shiret at
BZW was decidedly lukewarm about the figures and said: 'The results were in
line but I think the progress of the main WH Smith chain was muted.'
Presentations to institutions by Boots boosted the shares another 11 to
563p.
News that Body Shop is under investigation by US authorities in relation to
its US franchise operations left the shares trailing 8 to 219p.
MFI Furniture rose 3 to 149 1/2 p after BZW, a long term bear of the stock,
moved it from the sell list and gave it a hold recommendation following the
stocks' recent strong underperformance.
Kingfisher put on 6 to 534p, ahead of today's visit by institutions to one
of its warehouses.
Pharmaceuticals groups gained ground as takeover stories circulated in the
market. Wellcome, which is considered to be a prime bid candidate lifted 11
to 720p, with some additional help from the potential benefit from a legal
fracas with SmithKline Beecham, which fell 2 to 446p in the A's. Meanwhile
Zeneca which has also been mentioned as a potential UK target, improved 17
to 848p and Glaxo, considered to be looking for an acquisition, gained 7 1/2
to 652 1/2p.
Shell Transport improved 11 to 729p as SG Warburg discussed the group's
interim dividend prospects. The house was arguing that the company would
boost its UK dividend by 12 per cent to 11.4p and its full year payout by 16
per cent to 27 1/2 p putting the yield at a 15 per cent premium to the
market and giving a 10 per cent upside to the shares. Meanwhile, BP
benefited from news that it had successfully completed tests at its Cupigua
field in Colombia. The shares gained 6 to 412p.
Tobacco and insurance conglomerate BAT Industries improved 10 to 432p as
optimism over the prospects for tobacco profits in the US prompted Salomon
Brothers to upgrade its recommendation on rival Philip Morris. Shares in the
Telegraph sank 14 to 360p after the newspaper group revealed disappointing
first-half figures.
Among property stocks, Land Securities shed 3 to 649p on reports that
Kleinwort Benson had urged investors to switch out of the stock and into
MEPC, a penny harder at 454p. However, Kleinwort Benson denied making such a
recommendation.
Building materials group CAMAS, which was demerged from English China Clays
in June, put on 3 to 85p, following a UBS recommendation. English China shed
3 to 385p.
Information Technology group Parity gained 12 to 129p following a sharp rise
in interim profits to Pounds 2m.
Chemicals group Sutcliffe Speakman fell almost 20 per cent as the company
sacked its managing director and warned of poor sales in its carbons
division. The shares rallied to close 5 off at 40p.
Waste Management put on 6 to 585p ahead of a presentation to US and UK
analysts today.
Talk of an order and recommendation from Hoare Govett boosted defence
electronics group GEC. The shares added 6 to 301p, after trade of 4.7m.
Profit-taking in Senior Engineering which reported a 5 per cent profits
increase, in line with expectations, left the shares 14 1/2 down at 123 1/2
p.
There was poor sentiment among vehicle related stocks after Tuesday's
revelation of figures showing German car registrations down 16 per cent in
July. GKN lost 4 to 624p, while BBA Group eased 3 to 191p. Lucas Industries
relinquished 2 to 191p.
</TEXT>
<XX>
