<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Buy-back pushes RECs up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The regional electricity companies (RECs) saw their share prices spike
higher as Seeboard became the first since the recent regulatory review to
buy back its own equity.
The purchase of 2m shares at 425p in order to distribute part of its cash
surplus to shareholders represented less than one per cent of the company's
equity. It was a fragment of the stake that Seeboard can reclaim - it has
permission to buy back 10 per cent or 25m shares - but served as a timely
reminder of what one analyst described as the 'tiny window of opportunity'
that the RECs have.
Their closed seasons begin at the end of September and when they finally
report they will be inhibited by their involvement with the flotation of the
National Grid. This will take them through to the next closed season and
effectively tie their hands until next summer.
Mr Kevin Lapwood, of Smith New Court said: 'This is a dream ticket until the
end of September.' He believes prices could rise by 15 per cent in the short
term.
Hoare Govett take a more cautious stance but still believes share prices
could rise by a further 7 per cent. Profit taking towards the end of the day
saw some of the more spectacular rises whittled back but Seeboard closed 17
higher at 437p while Southern Electric rose 25 to 792p and Eastern
Electricity, which also experienced very active turnover in traded options,
added 20 at 822p. The gains are likely to dampen down some of the takeover
speculation that has surrounded the sector since Goldman Sachs bought a
block of 7.7m shares, some 2.99 per cent stake in Eastern, the sector
leader.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Seeboard.
    Southern Electric.
    Eastern Electricity.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4911 Electric Services.
</IN>
<XX>
