<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: London coffee futures lose
early gains as rally boils over - Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London COFFEE futures ended broadly unchanged after a volatile afternoon
marked by speculator and trade buying as well as technical selling and some
trade liquidation, dealers said.
The market, which was predicted to open Dollars 57 higher in the November
position following gains amounting to Dollars 250 earlier in the week, was
slightly firmer at midday but during the afternoon it swung from a day's
high of Dollars 3,650 a tonne to a low of Dollars 3,530.
At the close it stood at Dollars 3,573.
The London bullion market GOLD price broke through its previous resistance
area around Dollars 383 a troy ounce in early afternoon business as good
buying from the New York commission houses spilled over into Europe. It
closed at Dollars 384.25 an ounce, up Dollars 2.25.
Dealers were restrained in their enthusiasm, however. 'There's very little
physical interest around on gold at present, so I can't see this rally
lasting,' said one.
SILVER, underpinned by gold's move, broke through resistance to hit a high
of 534 cents an ounce before encountering selling.
Compiled from Reuters
