<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Government Bonds: Successful auction encourages Treasuries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Treasury bond prices jumped yesterday afternoon after a successful supply
auction allowed the market to build on its morning gains.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was up 15/16 at
100 1/2 , with the yield slipping to 7.457 per cent. At the short end, the
two-year note was  3/32 better at 100 3/32 , to yield 6.183 per cent.
Bonds forged ahead in the early hours after the Commerce Department
announced that factory orders of durable goods had plunged 4.2 per cent in
July.
Analysts were forecasting a slight increase, so the data came as a pleasant
surprise to traders anxious about any sign of economic acceleration, which
could erode the value of fixed-rate investments.
However, their enthusiasm was short-lived. Closer examination of the report
revealed that the unexpected weakness had stemmed primarily from a massive
drop in aircraft orders and a seasonal shutdown of automotive plants.
Excluding the volatile transportation component, the decline was relatively
tame.
After the market had time to digest the implications of the report, bond
prices receded to just above their opening values, even though a firmer
dollar was providing additional support.
The cautious mood reflected uncertainty over the outcome of the Treasury's
sale of Dollars 11bn in five-year notes later in the day. However, in the
event, the sale drew much better demand from retail accounts than
anticipated, allowing bonds to resume their forward advance in the final
hours of trading.
In the end, however, the day's gains were probably exaggerated by the
sluggish activity that characterises most summertime sessions.
The unexpected fall in US durable goods orders for July caused European
government bond markets to jump, but the rally was short-lived as
profit-taking set in almost immediately.
Analysts said it would have been dangerous for the markets to have read too
much into the fall, given the notorious volatility of this series. 'The
market shot up and then came back,' said Mr Adam Chester, international bond
strategist at Yamaichi. He said the fall in the data did not call for a
reassessment of the Federal Reserve's position on inflation.
The other main economic news of the day was the release of cost-of-living
data for August from two of Germany's most populous states. North
Rhine-Westphalia reported that prices were up 0.1 per cent in August for a
yearly increase of 2.8 per cent. Prices in Baden-Wuerttemberg rose 0.2 per
cent for an annual 3.1 per cent increase.
Although the market is still waiting for data from other states, analysts
said it was more than likely that the national figure would be at least 3
per cent. Even though the yearly rate should fall below 3 per cent later in
the year, it was inevitable that the downward progress on the inflation
front was slowing, now that the economy was picking up steam, they added.
'It is a swift reminder that the interest rate cycle is turning,' said Mr
Kit Juckes, international economist at SG Warburg.
On Liffe, the September bund future ended almost unchanged on the day, down
just 0.02 point at 91.41, well off the day's low of 91.60.
Sterling's recovery against the D-Mark helped to underpin the UK gilts
market, though trading remained thin. On Liffe, the September long gilt
future stood  3/16 point higher at 100 31/32 in late trading.
The recent stream of better-than-expected inflation and wage data has
prompted Kleinwort Benson to cut its 10-year gilt yield projection for
year-end from 9.25 per cent to 8.5 per cent.
'We are looking for gilts to outperform bunds and Treasuries from now until
the end of the year,' said Mr Julian Callow, European economist at Kleinwort
Benson.
He also noted that index-linked yields were now close to their 10-year
average of 3.8 per cent, and probably did not have much further to fall. 'As
a result, we would suggest a switch out of index-linked into conventional
gilts,' he said.
</TEXT>
