<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / International Company News: Blockbuster clears merger with
Viacom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The board of US video retailer Blockbuster Entertainment has approved the
merger of the company with Viacom, the entertainments group.
The decision ends months of uncertainty over the planned Dollars 8.4bn
union, which was conceived in January as part of Viacom's Dollars 10bn
takeover of Paramount Communications.
At the time, the structure of the stock-swap deal would have given
Blockbuster stockholders Dollars 31.50 a share.
However, a subsequent sharp drop in the value of Viacom stock - which was
plagued by concerns about how the group would pay off the more than Dollars
9bn in debt that it took on to acquire Paramount - drastically cut the value
of the deal for Blockbuster stockholders.
Instead of Dollars 31.50 a share, at one point they were faced with
accepting only Dollars 21.75 a share, and it was not long before Mr Wayne
Huizenga, Blockbuster chairman, and other leading stockholders began to have
second thoughts.
By May the deal looked dead, but a gradual recovery in Viacom's share price
over the summer (buoyed partly by the impressive performance of
Paramount-produced films at the box office) breathed new life into the
merger, and late on Tuesday Blockbuster's board approved the transaction.
The company's stockholders will now receive about Dollars 29 for each share.
</TEXT>
