<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / IBM picks up the gauntlet in the PC price war: The response
of rivals to Compaq's cuts is quickly gathering momentum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US personal computer market has been hit by 'Compaq Shock' as
competitors scramble to match last week's action by Compaq Computer that
reduced prices of many of its PCs by 11 to 22 per cent.
Yesterday, IBM announced broad price cuts of up to 27 per cent, matching
Compaq's new prices on most models and undercutting its rival by about 5 per
cent in the important 'PC server' segment.
The situation is reminiscent of the 'Compaq Shock' that hit the Japanese PC
market two years ago when Compaq dropped its prices and bulldozed its way
into a market formerly dominated by NEC. This time Compaq's targets are IBM
and Apple Computer - for many years the leading US PC suppliers. Compaq has
vowed to overtake them to become the world market leader by 1996.
Armed with Dollars 2.2bn (Pounds 1.4bn) worth of inventory which it hopes to
unleash on the market over the October to year-end quarter, typically the
peak PC selling season, Compaq is gearing up for battle.
With gross profit margins well above those of its competitors, Compaq can
afford to engage in a price war, say industry analysts. IBM has been quick
to respond to Compaq's price cuts and other leading PC makers are expected
to follow suit. Hewlett-Packard said yesterday that it would undercut
Compaq's new prices in about two weeks, while Digital Equipment has also
vowed to remain price competitive. The response of smaller PC companies is
less predictable. 'My gut feeling is that some competitors will react and
some will not. It depends on their overall strategy,' said Mr John Carlo
Bisone, Compaq's senior vice-president of North American marketing.
Compaq's attack comes at a particularly vulnerable time for its biggest
competitors. IBM is in the middle of restructuring its PC business while
Apple is making a transition to PowerPC microprocessor technology.
The price war could prove particularly costly to IBM, which is struggling to
regain momentum in the PC market. IBM's second-quarter US shipments dropped
29 per cent, as shipment volume at its four top rivals rose.
In the second quarter, Compaq had a 14.3 per cent share of the US market,
according to Dataquest. Apple Computer had an 11.2 per cent share; Packard
Bell Electronics had 9.3 per cent and IBM trailed at 7.9 per cent.
IBM's profit margins in the PC business are also well below those of Compaq,
which claims to be the market's lowest-cost producer. The new price cuts
will further reduce profit margins, but the company must respond to Compaq's
price challenge if it is not to see its market share dwindle.
Fuelling the battle in the PC industry are sharp price reductions by Intel,
the leading supplier of microprocessor chips. Over the past four months
Intel has lowered prices on its 486 and Pentium chips by about 40 per cent.
This has given PC makers an opportunity to trim their prices, while
maintaining profit margins.
Another factor that is adding momentum to the PC price war is the broad
availability of products. Over the past two years, PC makers have frequently
been unable to keep pace with demand for their products because of component
shortages. Most of these problems have now been solved and the industry has
a glut of products that it is anxious to unleash on the market.
The price cuts are also seen as a precursor to the introduction of new
products as the market shifts toward higher performance machines based on
Intel's Pentium microprocessors.
Television advertising will for the first time in several years become a
weapon in the looming PC marketing battle, with Compaq planning to double
its spending on US television commercials over the next three months and IBM
planning to return to TV advertising for the first time in years. Intel is
also planning its most ambitious TV advertising campaign to date.
'A fundamental shift in the market is taking place,' said Mr Dennis Carter,
Intel vice-president for marketing, adding that PC sales to home users are
exploding. In the fourth quarter of 1993, US sales of PCs to consumers
outstripped sales to businesses for the first time.
However, while Intel is aiming its marketing campaign at home PC users, the
focus of the PC pricing activities is in the corporate market, which
typically includes higher performance computers that command higher prices
and profit margins.
IBM's price cuts are particularly aggressive on 'PC servers'. The largest
IBM price drop is on a PC Server Array formerly priced at Dollars 13,090
which will now carry a list price of Dollars 9,500. This compares with
Compaq's price, on an equivalent PC server, of Dollars 10,000.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
