<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Seeboard share buy-back spurs Recs to new highs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in most regional electricity companies rose to record levels
yesterday after Crawley-based Seeboard joined what could become a rush by
the companies to buy back their own shares.
Yesterday's increases mean the companies have seen their market values rise
16 per cent on average in the two weeks since the industry regulator
announced a pricing regime generally regarded as favourable to the industry.
Yesterday's rises alone added Pounds 460m to the companies' market values
taking the total to more than Pounds 17bn. Analysts predicted further
increases immediately and in the long term.
Some said there could be falls for a short period after mid-October, when
share buy-backs would be ruled out before the annual results season.
However, others believe an expected announcement in October on the National
Grid, which the companies are likely to float on the stock market next
spring, could keep share prices high.
Seeboard is the second of the companies, after Eastern, to buy back its
shares but the first to do so since the regulator announced the pricing
review.
It made the purchases on Tuesday, paying 425p for 2m of its 257m shares in
issue. Like seven other regional companies Seeboard's shares, at 438p, up
17p, were at a record high last night.
All the regional companies have powers to buy back shares, mostly for up to
10 per cent of their equity, and all are well equipped financially to do so.
Each either has cash in hand or low borrowings. Buying back shares will
benefit earnings per share and the potential to increase dividend payments,
even if share prices rise further.
However the scope for effecting buy-backs is limited. Stock exchange rules
mean companies cannot pay more than 5 per cent above the average share price
on the previous 10 days.
That may be a constraint, with share prices rises. However, there should be
some days when prices fall and companies can buy in the market.
Postponing share buy-backs could mean a long delay as the companies will be
forbidden from trading their shares during the results season and,
potentially, after then because of the grid flotation. Knowledge of the
flotation details would give the companies insider knowledge.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
