<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Telegraph begins to feel price pain: Pre-tax profits slip
12% to Pounds 30.3m in first half and Conrad Black acknowledges 'severe
effects' of the cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Conrad Black, chairman of The Telegraph, said yesterday that price wars
in the UK's national newspaper industry represented the company's biggest
challenge since its move from Fleet Street eight years ago.
'We look forward to meeting that challenge,' said Mr Black as he announced a
12 per cent fall in interim pre-tax profits to Pounds 30.3m, from Pounds
34.6m, although the 1993 interim figures were helped by the sale of
investments.
The price-cutting war launched by Mr Rupert Murdoch's The Times has eaten
into Telegraph profits. The decision to counterattack, by cutting the
weekday price of the Daily Telegraph to 30p, cost the group Pounds 1m in the
six days of the change included in the six months accounting period to June
30. A further Pounds 1m was spent on a voucher scheme - a form of
discounting used before the price cut.
In addition, Pounds 8m was spent on promotion during the period to protect
the Daily Telegraph's circulation against the 20p Times.
Mr Black acknowledged yesterday that the 'severe effects' of the cover price
reduction would be reflected in group results in the shorter term, and
promotional costs to support the titles would continue to be significant.
'We are dedicated to maintaining the quality of our products and the
pre-eminence of these products in the newspaper advertising industry,' said
Mr Black.
Since the Daily Telegraph cut its price, circulation has increased from
about 993,000 to 1.07m.
Mr Black added that areas had been identified where costs could be saved.
Promotion expenses, for example, would be reduced in the second half.
Mr Stephen Grabiner, the Telegraph's managing director, said the irony was
that the new readers were largely the young people the Telegraph had tried
and failed to attract in the past.
'We could end up with a better readership profile as a result of this. That
is the only good news there is now.' Mr Grabiner added that the company
could not 'afford to blink' in the price wars.
The drop in UK circulation revenues of around 4 per cent was offset by good
results from the John Fairfax newspaper group in Australia, an associate
company. The contributions from associates more than doubled from Pounds
4.4m to Pounds 11.8m.
Operating profit at The Telegraph was down by Pounds 3.5m at Pounds 20.3m.
Earnings per share were 15.8p. This compared with 13.4p excluding the
effects of investment sales and 16.6p including them.
The interim dividend remains unchanged at 5.5p.
John Fairfax results, Page 22
</TEXT>
