<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / W H Smith confident on book law change: Charges reduce
annual pre-tax profits to Pounds 83m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WH Smith, the retailing group, said yesterday it was confident it could
withstand the possible removal of the net book agreement, which keeps book
prices at fixed levels in the UK. It also reported a fall in annual pre-tax
profits from Pounds 113.8m to Pounds 83.4m.
Sir Malcolm Field, chief executive, said last week's decision by the Office
of Fair Trading to refer the net book agreement to the restrictive practices
court was not a cause for concern.
'We have not got hard figures as to what life would be like without the
agreement. What we have got is a strategy for prospering without it,' he
said. WH Smith had experience of a price-competitive book market in the US,
and was confident of recouping lost gross margin by increasing UK market
share, if price-cutting were legalised.
The full-year results were hit by exceptional costs of Pounds 36.6m for
rationalisation of Do It All, the DIY joint venture with Boots, denting an
otherwise encouraging performance. Adding back those costs and Pounds 6m of
restructuring charges for the WH Smith chain - offset by Pounds 1.2m profits
on disposals - underlying pre-tax profits were up 13 per cent at Pounds
124.8m.
Sir Malcolm said capital expenditure would be a record Pounds 140m this
year. Some Pounds 50m would be spent on adding 230,000 sq ft of selling
space to the existing 3.5m sq ft.
Group sales for the 52 weeks to May 28 increased 5.6 per cent to Pounds
2.44bn. Since then sales and profits were 'marginally ahead', in spite of
consumer caution.
Sales in the UK retail division, including WH Smith, Waterstones, Our Price
and Virgin, increased 4.8 per cent to Pounds 1.35bn, with operating profits
up 9.1 per cent to Pounds 93.8m.
Losses at Do It All fell from Pounds 14.3m to Pounds 10.5m. The chain is
being reduced to a 'core' of 137 stores and is expected to return to profit
next year.
Profits in the distribution business rose 13.6 per cent to Pounds 37.7m, on
sales up 5.9 per cent at Pounds 1.02bn.
In the US, sales grew 11.3 per cent to Pounds 223m, and profits 7.3 per cent
to Pounds 11.8m. The group plans to expand Waterstones in the US.
A final dividend of 10.4p lifts the total payout 8.5 per cent to 15.4p.
Earnings per share, after exceptional items, fell from 31.1p to 20.2p.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
