<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / US fund irked by Body Shop reaction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US ethical investment fund that sold its shares in Body Shop
International has criticised the cosmetics and toiletries group for the way
in which the fund's views have been represented.
Franklin Research and Development, the Boston-based organisation, said
yesterday that - contrary to Body Shop's assertions - its concerns about the
company's green and ethical image were among the reasons for its decision to
sell.
News of Franklin's decision to dispose of 50,000 Body Shop shares and to
recommend its clients to do likewise has triggered an intense debate. It has
also prompted Body Shop to claim that Franklin had said its views had been
misrepresented in the press.
However, Mr Patrick McVeigh, Franklin's senior vice president, said
yesterday his organisation had been put under pressure by Body Shop, and was
'not pleased' by the way its views had been characterised.
His comments follow suggestions that Franklin decided to sell its shares
purely on commercial grounds: because of competition and the potential
impact of allegations - expected to be published in the US press - on the
share price. 'We certainly had ethical concerns, if not we would not have
sold the stock,' he said. 'We do not sell stock based on every short-term
rumour.'
One article is expected in Business Ethics magazine next week. Franklin is
also in discussions with Body Shop over an article in its own newsletter and
over any revised recommendation - it is still advising clients to sell.
Mr McVeigh said Body Shop's behaviour towards Franklin 'could not help but
influence' its final assessment of the company.
Body Shop yesterday confirmed it had held discussions with the US Federal
Trade Commission, which is investigating disputes with franchisees. It had
received one request for information from the FTC nine months ago with which
it had co-operated fully.
'Any federal agency in the US upon receiving a complaint - whatever the
source - is forced to investigate.' Many franchisees were asking for more
shops. 'This is hardly a system in disarray.' Mr Gordon Roddick, chairman,
expressed frustration at 'innuendo' from 'the zealots of cynicism'.
</TEXT>
