<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Accountants face tough new monitoring rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Accountants in public practice would be subject to tough new monitoring and
continuing education requirements, under sweeping proposals released
yesterday by their leading professional bodies.
All accountants in positions of influence holding a practising certificate
would be required to continue to attend training every year if they were to
retain their licence to operate.
A small proportion of accountants outside the existing regulated areas would
also become subject to monitoring for the first time.
The proposals come in a document from the professional standards review
working party, comprising members of the three professional chartered
accountancy bodies covering England and Wales, Scotland and Ireland. Under
existing regulations, accountants offering investment advice, auditing
services and insolvency have become subject to regular examination by
self-regulatory bodies.
However, the proposals suggest introducing powers to allow accountancy
institutes to examine members of firms outside these areas, and to inspect
practices offering additional services such as tax advice.
Those most likely to be inspected would be those handling clients' money.
This would be to ensure their compliance with existing regulations. It might
also include any other practices to which the institutes were alerted by
complaints from the public.
Mr Bruce Picking, director of practice regulation at the Institute of
Chartered Accountants in England and Wales, stressed that only a small
proportion of firms would be subject to inspection - perhaps 3 per cent of
the total.
Every 'principal' in an accountancy practice - which ranges from the sole
practitioner to any partner in a large firm - is presently required to hold
a practising certificate.
Under the present system, all requirements for continuing education cease
once the certificate has been awarded. Accountants who qualified before 1974
are not even required to complete the education requirements, and others
qualifying before 1978 can claim exemptions.
The changes would allow certificates to be issued subject to certain
potentially wide-ranging conditions. The institutes expect to conclude
discussions on the proposals in January and begin implementation in early
1996.
Role of auditing submerged by small print, Page 8
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8721 Accounting, Auditing, and Bookkeeping Services.
    P8611 Business Associations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
